The paper presents a framework for learning human user models for collaborative tasks with a robot, which involves clustering action sequences, learning reward functions, and incorporating them into a mixed-observability Markov decision process (MOMDP) formulation. This work is highly relevant to the field of robotics (cs.RO) as it focuses on developing a framework for human-robot collaboration. Additionally, the use of unsupervised learning and inverse reinforcement learning algorithms for clustering and reward function learning respectively, suggests a strong presence of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) in the paper. The paper also discusses the use of a human subject experiment, indicating a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The use of a MOMDP formulation suggests a focus on control and systems engineering (cs.SY), and the use of machine learning algorithms suggests a focus on machine learning (cs.LG).
